an innovative understanding of what it means to be healthy in postcolonial Latin America. Through vivid descriptions of how people reject global standards and embrace fatness as desirable, this book interferes with contemporary biomedicine, adding depth to how we theorize structural violence. It is essential reading for anyone who cares about the politics of healthy eating.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDietzGuatemala. 0aFood consumptionzGuatemala. 0aFood habitszGuatemala. 0aObesityxSocial aspectszGuatemala. 0aObesityzGuatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  acontemporary biomedicine.  adiabetes.  adiet in guatemala.  afat studies.  afatness.  afood habits guatemala.  aglobal health.  aguatemalan diet.  aguatemalan health.  ahealth and medicine.  ahealth impacts of obesity.  ahealthy eating.  ahealthy food habits.  ahealthy guatemala.  ahealthy latin america.  ahigh blood pressure.  ahypertension.  ainternational food studies.  alatin american health.  anutrition.  aobesity.  aoverweight.  apolicing food.  apolitics of food.  apostcolonial latin america.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028681840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096190640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961906423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961906/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY